# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Replacing Outliers and Missing Values¶

In [24]:
for x in ['CoapplicantIncome','ApplicantIncome','LoanAmount','Loan_Amount_Term']:
    q75,q25 = np.percentile(df_num.loc[:,x],[75,25])
    intr_qr = q75-q25
 
    max = q75+(1.5*intr_qr)
    min = q25-(1.5*intr_qr)
 
    df_num.loc[df_num[x] < min,x] = np.nan
    df_num.loc[df_num[x] > max,x] = np.nan

Elbow Curve¶

In [39]:
clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / subset_scaled_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)

Silhouette scores¶

In [40]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((subset_scaled_df))
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

Insights¶

Cluster 0:¶

Applicants' incomes are a bit more than average, and Co-applicants' incomes are average. Loan amount is moderate. Loan amount term is the lowest. It is the smallest group.

Cluster 1:¶

Applicants' incomes is the highest while the Co-applicants' incomes is the lowest. Loan amount is high. Loan amount term is exactly the same as the other two clusters(2 and 3).

Cluster 2:¶

Applicants' incomes and the Co-applicants' incomes are moderate and have almost similar amounts. Loan amount is the highest. Loan amount term is exactly the same as the other two clusters(1 and 3). It is the biggest cluster.

Cluster 3:¶

Applicants' incomes is moderate and the Co-applicants' incomes is low. Loan amount is the lowest. Loan amount term is exactly the same as the other two clusters(1 and 2).

Business Recommendations¶

Cluster 2: The loan customers in this group have a moderate income also; their co-applicant income is the highest among other co-applicants. Their loan amount is the highest, and they are the biggest group of applicants. So, because the number of this group is high, and they have high-income co-applicants, banks should focus on this group as they are potential low-risk customers.¶

Cluster 1:The loan applicants in this cluster have a very high income, but their co-applicant income is very low. Their loan amount is high, and they are the second-largest group of applicants. The second important group is this one because they have a high income to be able to pay off their loans, and their risk is low.¶

Cluster 0:This group is customers with an average income, both themselves and their co-applicants. Their loan amount is less than 10K, and their number is not very much.¶

Cluster 3: This group includes clients with the lowest amount of loans. Their income is moderate, and their co-applicants income is low. Their number is not very much either. This group is high risk because neither the applicant nor the co-applicant has a high income and might be a defaulter.¶
